<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING BRIEFING: AND IN THE SEVENTH THEY SANG, 'TAKE ME OUT TO THE WALLGAME' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 All that remains of Forbes Field in Pittsburgh is the outfield wall, and it's 
a gathering place for baseball zealots who make a pilgrimage to the site each 
Oct 13.  
</P>
<P>
 They come there to reminisce on the day Bill Mazeroski hit a home run in 1960 
to beat the New York Yankees in the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
 "Fans took peanuts and popcorn, tapes of the game, original programs and other 
memorabilia to the anniversary celebration," writes Beth E. Trapani of the 
Pittsburgh Post-Gazette. 
</P>
<P>
 "They wore Pirate hats and shirts and huddled around a cassette recorder as if 
listening to the game for the first time." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Trivia time: Joe DiMaggio and his brothers Dominic and Vince had the same 
middle name. What was it? 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Oiler misery: Before the Houston Oilers lost to the Philadelphia Eagles, 21-6, 
on Monday night, defensive tackle Ray Childress said: 
</P>
<P>
 "I think we're a bad 1-5, and that's the hard part to take." 
</P>
<P>
 The Oilers are now a bad 1-6. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Add Oilers: Wide receiver Ernest Givins: "You could bring in Jimmy Johnson, 
Vince Lombardi and Tom Landry and it's not going to change anything this 
season." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Just wondering: Tom Weir in USA Today: "Who would have thought UNLV would be 
looking back on the Jerry Tarkanian era as the Running' Rebels quiet years?" 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Wait a minute: Alex Smith, Indiana University freshman tailback, talking about 
his 40-yard dash time in an interview with Bill Jauss of the Chicago Tribune: 
</P>
<P>
 "I've been clocked in some 4.3s (seconds). Consistently in 4.4." 
</P>
<P>
 If so, then Smith is wasting his time in football. That's world-class speed -- 
Bob Hayes and Carl Lewis company. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Court graveyard: Dallas Maverick forward Jamal Mashburn on former Coach Quinn 
Buckner's triangle offense: 
</P>
<P>
 "That was a nightmare. I called it the Bermuda Triangle. We didn't have a clue 
what we were doing." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Modesty: Charles Barkley, when asked to talk about the talent on the Phoenix 
Suns: 
</P>
<P>
 "We don't have any superstars on this team . . . except me. I don't worry 
about it. I just do my thing and hope they can catch up." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Binding edict: Minutes from a 1941 NFL Public Relations clinic: 
</P>
<P>
 "In keeping publicity on a high, dignified plane, club publicity men are 
charged with the responsibility of preventing coaches from endorsing liquor, 
cigarettes or laxatives." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Looking back: On this day in 1984, Rueben Mayes of Washington State set an 
NCAA record with 357 yards rushing in a 50-41 victory over Oregon. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Trivia answer: Paul. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Quotebook: Peter Karmanos, principal owner of the Hartford Whalers, on the NHL 
labor dispute: "It's not my career that's ticking away." MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
</TEXT>
