COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: FULLERTON; COUNCIL APPROVES HOUSING FOR DISABLED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIMI KO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 City Council members have given developers approval to build an 
affordable-housing complex for people with disabilities. 
</P>
<P>
 The developer, Rehabilitation Institute of Southern California, will offer the 
25 apartment units at monthly rents ranging from $379 to $618, including 
utility costs. 
</P>
<P>
 As a condition of approval, the rents must remain at comparable levels for 99 
years. Also, the city Redevelopment Agency will spend about $39,000 upgrading a 
water main at the 2.12-acre site. 
</P>
<P>
 The apartment complex will share its address, 2200 E. Chapman Ave., with 
another soon-to-be constructed project -- a 27-unit apartment complex for 
lower-income people that drew complaints from dozens of residents who said it 
would create traffic problems. 
</P>
<P>
 The apartments for the disabled, however, prompted no such opposition and 
received unanimous approval from the council. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a worthwhile project," Councilman Chris Norby said. "It addresses a 
specific need group." 
</P>
<P>
 Completion of the project is expected by the end of 1996, officials said.MIMI 
KO 
