<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: MOORPARK; SCHOOL BOARD VOTES AGAINST PROP. 187 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MACK REED 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saying Proposition 187 could kick 360 local students out of school, the 
Moorpark school board has unanimously opposed the "Save Our State" ballot 
initiative that would deny educational services to illegal immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
 However, the board failed to support a "conscientious objector" clause 
suggested by member Tom Baldwin. Baldwin said that the board should not 
discipline teachers who refuse to follow Proposition 187's requirement that 
they report students who are illegal immigrants to authorities. 
</P>
<P>
 "Why should a person have to risk their job to follow a law that is immoral?" 
Baldwin said in an interview. "I don't think we should be putting our employees 
in that position where they have to make a choice between their job and doing 
something they consider wrong." 
</P>
<P>
 But the proposal died for lack of a second. 
</P>
<P>
 "Obviously there was no support on the board to allow civil disobedience," 
trustee Pam Castro said. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials estimate that Proposition 187 could cost the Moorpark district 
$644,000 in state funds and $500,000 in federal funds each year. It also could 
force the district to spend about $60,000 to verify immigration status of 
students, about 28% of whom are Latino and 6% of whom may be illegal 
immigrants, Baldwin said. 
</P>
<P>
 The board resolution also contends that Proposition 187 is illegal because the 
U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that undocumented immigrants cannot be denied a 
public education. However, the Yes on 187 coordinator for Ventura County 
scoffed at the resolution, saying it will have little effect on popular support 
for the measure. 
</P>
<P>
 "Every city and school district opposed Proposition 13. (But) the people 
didn't care, they wanted to save their homes," said political consultant Steve 
Frank. "In this case, Proposition l87, the people don't care what the 
bureaucrats and elected politicians say, they want to save their tax dollars." 
MACK REED 
</P>
</TEXT>
